	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Lloyd Gordon</b> [ Wed Sep 26, 2007 9:35 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>SMD Resistor Fix Pictures</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />First you carefully cut the traces from connector 7-13 under where the SMD resistors are now. I did it slightly away from the resistor IC so the solder won't flow over the cut in the trace when you solder in the SMD resistors. You have to tin the traces after you cut them before you solder the SMD resistors in. Try not to glop on the connector as I did. I used a small low power tip and soldered the resistors right to the globs on the IC resistor to make them more secure.
<br />
<br />Then solder the other end of the SMD resistor. Check with a multimeter. I would use 100-120 Ohm if you can get them. I only found 150 Ohm at my local store.
<br />
<br />Note the second picture. You have to cut connector trace #6 on the <span style="text-decoration: underline">component side</span>. You can figure out why if you follow the connections to that lead.
<br />
<br />I used a fine curved forceps to hold the resistors but a toothpick would probably be Ok.
<br />
<br /><a href="http://xs.to/xs.php?h=xs319&amp;d=07393&amp;f=SMD.JPG" class="postlink"><img src="http://xs319.xs.to/xs319/07393/SMD.JPG.xs.jpg" alt="Image" /></a>
<br />Back Side
<br /><a href="http://xs.to/xs.php?h=xs319&amp;d=07393&amp;f=Trace.JPG" class="postlink"><img src="http://xs319.xs.to/xs319/07393/Trace.JPG.xs.jpg" alt="Image" /></a>
<br />Component Side

		

